# GKD-BNF

`pip install gkdbnf`.

Maybe the most simplest way to write pretty BNF in LaTex.

Use this package with `gkdtex`:

```tex
\gkd@usepackage{gkdbnf}

\gkd@bnf{
<i> :: Integer

!Instructions! <l> :: !Instr[MinSIL]! = \mathbf{load} \; i  %%% describe load
                                     |  \mathbf{store} \; i
                                     |  \mathbf{push} \; \zeta
                                     |  \mathbf{pop}
                                     |  \cdots
}
```

## Syntax


Valid BNF Syntax:
```bnf
atom ::= NONTERMINAL
       | TERMINAL
       | TERMINAL2
       | '|'

rule        ::= '%%%' TERMINAL2
description ::=  TERMINAL | TERMINAL2
type        ::= TERMINAL | TERMINAL2 | NONTERMINAL

prod  ::= description? NONTERMINAL '::' type  '=' atom+ rule? 
      | '|' atom+ rule?

start ::= start NEWLINE
      |   start prod
      |   NEWLINE
      |   prod
```


Lexer rule by regex:
```
NEWLINE     = [\r\n]+
NONTERMINAL = <.*?>
TERMINAL2   = !.*?!
TERMINAL    = \S+
```

Whitespace tokens are ignored.

## Nice Error Report
```tex 
1:  \gkd@usepackage{gkdbnf}
2:  \gkd@bnf{
3:  <a> ::= a + 1
4:
5:  <c> ::= a a
6:  Expressions e ::= e
7: }
```

You get error

```
SyntaxError: filename runtest/a.tex:
line 6, column 13, NonTerm not match
```

Then you know you should change `Expression e` to `Expression <e>`.


